    THIS FILE'S ROLE IN THE OVERALL POC
    ===================================
    This report is the urgency-tier-distribution bar chart shown on the
    Manager View dashboard
    (../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_casemgmt_manager_view.xml). It sits
    alongside four other widgets to give a manager a complete operational
    picture of the team's case portfolio:

      - "All Cases by Status" bar chart
        (../reports/x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_status.xml) shows the
        DISTRIBUTION across the lifecycle (Draft, Open, In Progress,
        Pending, Resolved, Closed) - lifecycle-stage view.
      - "All Cases by Type" donut/pie chart
        (../reports/x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_type.xml) shows the
        SUBDOMAIN MIX between General Inquiry and Complaint -
        case-handling-pipeline view.
      - THIS bar chart shows the DISTRIBUTION across urgency tiers
        (Low, Medium, High, Critical) - urgency-tier view. Managers
        use it to assess whether the team is over-indexed on
        Critical/High volume (signals operational stress, a need for
        triage policy or staffing changes) or whether Low/Medium
        cases dominate (signals normal intake mix). Comparative bar
        heights against a common baseline make the relative volume
        across the four ordinal urgency tiers immediately readable.
      - "Average Time to Close" single-score widget
        (../reports/x_casemgmt_avg_time_to_close.xml) shows the
        operational throughput KPI.
      - "Cases Opened in Last 30 Days" single-score widget
        (../reports/x_casemgmt_cases_opened_30d.xml) shows the
        intake-volume KPI.

    Together the five widgets satisfy the Manager View dashboard goal
    per AAP Section 0.4.4: "demonstrate that a case_manager ... see
    operationally relevant aggregate views on day one".

    SEMANTIC SOURCE-SIDE ANCHOR (READ-ONLY, NOT BYTE-FOR-BYTE PORTED)
    =================================================================
    The semantic ancestors of this report in the existing ArkCase
    codebase are two Java artifacts in the case-file-plugin:

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/
        java/com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java
        Lines 178-179:
            @Column(name = "cm_case_priority")
            private String priority;
        ArkCase tracked case priority as a free-form String column on
        the `acm_case_file` MySQL table. The value space was not
        constrained at the JPA level; ArkCase relied on
        application-level conventions to enforce consistency. The
        ServiceNow target normalizes this to a Choice field with four
        explicit ordinal values per AAP Section 0.5.7 (Low, Medium,
        High, Critical) defined in
        ../choices/sys_choice_case_priority.xml. The
        <group_by>priority</group_by> below references this Choice
        field by element name; the bar chart renders one vertical bar
        per distinct Choice label.

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/
        java/com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseByStatusDto.java
        Lines 33-57:
            public class CaseByStatusDto {
                private String status;
                private int    count;
                ... getters and setters ...
            }
        The (key, count) DTO that ArkCase produced for status-aggregation
        reports - the same shape applies generalized to priority:
        a (priority, count) tuple consumed by Pentaho-backed reports.
        The ServiceNow target replaces this DTO + Pentaho pipeline with
        a native sys_report whose `<group_by>priority</group_by>` plus
        `<aggregate>COUNT</aggregate>` produce the same tuple shape
        directly via the platform's GlideAggregate engine - no DTO,
        no external BI tool, no Solr facet. The dashboard widget
        renders the (priority, count) pairs as bars.

    Per AAP Section 0.1.2 ("Reporting transformation: Pentaho BI +
    Solr aggregates -> ServiceNow Reports + Performance Analytics-style
    dashboards"), the ServiceNow target replaces Pentaho-driven
    dimensional aggregation with platform-native sys_report records
    (this file plus the seven sibling reports in this folder), all
    powered by ServiceNow's native GlideAggregate engine instead of an
    external BI engine.

    DESIGN DECISIONS LOCKED IN BY THIS FILE
    =======================================
      - Aggregation discipline (AAP Section 0.5.1, this report's row):
        type = bar. Per agent-prompt Mandatory Field Specification,
        chart-type reports populate <type>, <group_by>, and <aggregate>;
        they leave <field_list/> and <aggregation_source/> empty. The
        rendered output is one vertical-bar chart with one bar per
        distinct value of `priority`.

      - Group-by discipline (agent-prompt Rule 4 verbatim):
        <group_by>priority</group_by>. The Choice field defined in
        ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_priority.xml. The four bars
        correspond to the four Choice values defined in
        ../choices/sys_choice_case_priority.xml: Low, Medium, High,
        Critical (Title Case, single ASCII tokens - NOT "low",
        NOT "LOW", NOT "Critical-Priority", NOT numeric 1/2/3/4).

      - Filter discipline (agent-prompt Rule 5 verbatim):
        <filter/> empty. This report counts ALL cases regardless of
        status, type, or assignment. The Manager View dashboard is
        intentionally an unfiltered aggregate-perspective view -
        per-viewer filtering belongs to Agent Workspace's "My Open
        Cases" list (../reports/x_casemgmt_my_open_cases.xml) and
        "My Overdue Tasks" list
        (../reports/x_casemgmt_my_overdue_tasks.xml). This bar chart
        retains terminal-state cases (Resolved, Closed) because the
        Manager View needs visibility into the historical distribution
        of priorities across the full team backlog to inform staffing
        and triage policy.

      - Aggregation discipline (agent-prompt Rule 6 verbatim):
        <aggregate>COUNT</aggregate>. Counts records per priority
        bucket. <aggregation_source/> empty (COUNT does not require a
        numeric source field; it counts rows, not values).

      - Field-list discipline (agent-prompt Rule 9 verbatim):
        <field_list/> empty. Chart reports do NOT specify a field list;
        the field list is meaningful only for `type=list` reports per
        the sibling pattern in ../reports/x_casemgmt_my_open_cases.xml
        (which uses a comma-separated <field_list> for column display).
        For chart reports, the chart-type and group-by fully determine
        what is rendered.

      - Per-viewer semantics: this report does NOT reference any
        user-specific identity (e.g., gs.getUserID()); it returns the
        SAME aggregated counts for every viewer. Therefore:
          1) The platform does not need to re-compute the aggregate
             per-user, only per-cache-cycle.
             <is_real_time>false</is_real_time> below permits cached
             evaluation.
          2) Different roles see the same numbers (modulo what their
             ACL permits them to read). For a `case_viewer`, all four
             bars appear (read-all ACL). For a `case_agent`, only
             bars for cases assigned to them or their group appear
             (assigned-only ACL per AAP Section 0.5.6). For a
             `case_manager`, all four bars appear (full ACL). The
             Manager View dashboard is gated to `case_manager` per
             AAP Section 0.4.4, so the typical viewer sees the full
             team picture.

      - Why "type=bar" not "type=pie" (agent-prompt Rule 8 verbatim):
        per AAP Section 0.4.4 the Manager View dashboard pairs
        different chart types to different cardinalities of
        categorical data:
          - Status (6 buckets): bar chart - magnitude comparison
            across many discrete buckets favors absolute-count
            readability.
          - Priority (4 buckets): bar chart - same rationale at lower
            cardinality; ordinal urgency tiers benefit from left-to-
            right linear ordering. Comparative bar heights against
            a common baseline make ordinal differences (e.g., is the
            Critical pile larger than the High pile?) immediately
            readable, which a radial pie/donut would obscure for
            small relative differences. Per the agent prompt's
            Key Insight #2: "four discrete buckets (Low/Medium/High/
            Critical) read better with comparative bar heights than
            as pie slices".
          - Type (2 buckets, extensible): donut/pie chart -
            proportion comparison across a small number of buckets
            favors "what percentage is each?" readability.
        The deliberate diversity of chart types is a UX-quality
        decision per AAP Section 0.4.4 and is NOT to be flattened
        into "all bar" or "all pie" for consistency.

      - Cache discipline: <is_real_time>false</is_real_time>. The
        platform may cache the aggregated counts and refresh on a
        cycle (typically 5 minutes for the Reports module). For a
        POC dashboard with 10 demo cases this distinction is
        cosmetic; for a production case-management deployment with
        thousands of cases it materially affects dashboard load
        time. The default-off setting matches the sibling reports
        (../reports/x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_status.xml,
         ../reports/x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_type.xml,
         ../reports/x_casemgmt_case_count_by_status.xml,
         ../reports/x_casemgmt_my_open_cases.xml,
         ../reports/x_casemgmt_avg_time_to_close.xml,
         ../reports/x_casemgmt_cases_opened_30d.xml).

      - Chart-size discipline: <chart_size>medium</chart_size>. The
        platform-default rendering size for embedded dashboard
        widgets. Matches the sibling reports.

      - Scope binding: <sys_scope>x_casemgmt</sys_scope> and
        <sys_package source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
        bind THIS record to the same scoped-app row that the parent
        sys_app record (../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml)
        publishes via the sys_scope record at
        ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml (where <name>x_casemgmt</name>
        and <source>x_casemgmt</source>). Cross-file consistency: the
        sibling reports (x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_status.xml,
        x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_type.xml,
        x_casemgmt_case_count_by_status.xml,
        x_casemgmt_my_open_cases.xml, x_casemgmt_my_overdue_tasks.xml,
        x_casemgmt_avg_time_to_close.xml,
        x_casemgmt_cases_opened_30d.xml) use identical scope-reference
        values, ensuring all reports resolve to the same sys_app row
        at preview time. Reference-by-name not reference-by-sys_id
        per AAP Section 0.7.2 (no hardcoded sys_ids constraint).

      - <sys_id> determinism: the value
        f4c76c4c0bb1643542ac6347ddf9edcd is the lowercase MD5 of the
        canonical record name "x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_priority". This
        matches the convention documented in
        ../reports/x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_status.xml lines 250-273
        (md5("x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_status") = deeaca81d8626c9c2cc2974716efd08c),
        ../reports/x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_type.xml lines 232-253
        (md5("x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_type") = f35f0a22b19d6e5385538eb3febb1a84),
        ../reports/x_casemgmt_case_count_by_status.xml lines 223-242
        (md5("x_casemgmt_case_count_by_status") = 32ae52ab8735ea76587edee6130abc06),
        ../reports/x_casemgmt_my_open_cases.xml lines 219-236
        (md5("x_casemgmt_my_open_cases") = ee04fa982b136ad35c6fe1512826f6ab),
        ../reports/x_casemgmt_avg_time_to_close.xml lines 233-247
        (md5("x_casemgmt_avg_time_to_close") = 79fabb5f5754b629205b2382face3ebb),
        and ../reports/x_casemgmt_cases_opened_30d.xml lines 71-84
        (md5("x_casemgmt_cases_opened_30d") = 95b2127b026a92ba5e041a8d4d7277ec).
        Deterministic derivation makes the Update Set re-importable
        on a fresh PDI without sys_id collisions: re-importing the
        same XML on the same or any future PDI resolves the same
        sys_id and idempotently updates the same report row rather
        than creating a duplicate. This stability is REQUIRED because
        the Manager View dashboard
        (../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_casemgmt_manager_view.xml)
        references THIS report by `<name>x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_priority</name>`,
        and the dashboard widget binding must resolve consistently
        across re-imports.

